04717nam a22007215i 9780226341477DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016058657  a9780226341477  a(DE-B1597)525064  a(OCoLC)1005637674  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aPN4864b.G83 2017 4aPN4864 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a071.3090342231 aGuarneri, Julia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNewsprint Metropolis :bCity Papers and the Making of Modern Americans /cJulia Guarneri. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (368 p.) :b8 color plates, 59 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHistorical Studies of Urban America00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- tOne: A New Newspaper Model -- tTwo: Making Metropolitans -- tThree: Building Print Community -- tFour: Connecting City, Suburb, and Region -- tFive: Nationalizing the News -- tEpilogue -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the close of the nineteenth century, new printing and paper technologies fueled an expansion of the newspaper business. Newspapers soon saturated the United States, especially its cities, which were often home to more than a dozen dailies apiece. Using New York, Philadelphia, Milwaukee, and Chicago as case studies, Julia Guarneri shows how city papers became active agents in creating metropolitan spaces and distinctive urban cultures. Newsprint Metropolis offers a vivid tour of these papers, from the front to the back pages. Paying attention to much-loved features, including comic strips, sports pages, advice columns, and Sunday magazines, she tells the linked histories of newspapers and of the cities they served. Guarneri shows how themed sections for women, businessmen, sports fans, and suburbanites illustrated entire ways of life built around consumer products. But while papers provided a guide to individual upward mobility, they also fostered a climate of civic concern and responsibility. Charity campaigns and metropolitan sections painted portraits of distinctive, cohesive urban communities. Real estate sections and classified ads boosted the profile of the suburbs, expanding metropolitan areas while maintaining cities’ roles as economic and information hubs. All the while, editors were drawing in new reading audiences—women, immigrants, and working-class readers—helping to give rise to the diverse, contentious, and commercial public sphere of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAmerican newspapersxHistoryy19th century. 0aAmerican newspapersxHistoryy20th century. 0aAmerican newspapersxSocial aspects. 0aAmerican newspapers--History--19th century. 0aCities and townszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aCity dwellerszUnited States. 0aNews audienceszUnited States. 0aUrbanizationzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aUrbanizationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aCivic.  aFeature.  aJournalism.  aMedia.  aMetropolis.  aMetropolitan.  aNewspaper.  aUrban.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUrban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019z978311063851640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226341477423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226341477/original  a978-3-11-063851-6  Urban Studies and Social Rights eBook Package PP 2016-2019c2016d2019  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyt